{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3bdb094e-43e3-4ef2-a36a-6f3b52e85b23","content":"Here's what I found:\n\n**`my_app/views.py:3`** — `datetime.now()` called directly inside a view function:\n\n```python\nnow = datetime.now()\n```\n\nThis is hard to test because you can't control the clock without monkeypatching.\n\n### Recommendations\n\n1. **Use Django's `timezone.now()`** — it's timezone-aware and easier to mock via `django.utils.timezone`:\n   ```python\n   from django.utils import timezone\n   now = timezone.now()\n   ```\n\n2. **Inject the clock** — accept a callable so tests can substitute it:\n   ```python\n   def index(request, clock=timezone.now):\n       now = clock()\n   ```\n\n3. **Use `freezegun`** — the `@freeze_time(\"2026-01-01\")` decorator lets you pin time in tests without changing production code.\n\nOnly one file with one occurrence was found in the project. Would you like me to refactor it?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5619f5e7-c657-4d48-964f-938c3b6d09e0","outputTokens":231,"requestId":"BC27:A067E:2007A7D:23E18C1:69FAA982"},"id":"c14b63ab-7a8f-4502-8ea6-28c1be452bca","timestamp":"2026-05-06T02:38:01.137Z","parentId":"56061087-a26b-4af8-b1bd-567c2b4e34ed"}
